narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course? (Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: Deep knowledge and understanding of the origins of the second world war and historical memory, as well as skills in research and essay writing.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved? (Your anonymous response to this question may be viewed by Yale College students, faculty, and advisers to aid in course selection and evaluating teaching.)
comments: Excellent class, Paul Kennedy is a great professor whose knowledge of the topic is literally unmatched
Professor Kennedy is brilliant and the course is fantastic. The only way it might be improved is if there was more contemporary, focused reading.

The course did an excellent job conveying the key themes that ran throughout the series of crises, incidents, and conflicts which spanned the interwar years. These helped me make sense of and better put into order the sequence of events to think more strategically about this period. However, in my opinion the class often was heavily comprised of student presentations which took up most of the time, I wish that perhaps there could have been fewer, or at least shorter, presentations to leave more time for all the students to dig into the readings for the week and discuss the topics among ourselves.

comments: Yes, but make sure you go into the course with something you want to take out of it (a paper topic, an area about which you want to learn more, etc.) because Kennedy tailors the course to his students interests
Yes - legendary professor and a great course
